    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-25T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-25T21:00:00-05:00" n="137"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Kulangsu/154: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Amoy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVitty</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Amoy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-26T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 26, 1939—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 26—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>39. Indications this morning are that the abrupt termination of the naval
                    conferences by Admiral Noble yesterday took the Japanese by complete surprise
                    and that they are now in a much more conciliatory mood and the prospects of a
                    solution of the situation are at present more hopeful.</p>
                <p>The Japanese have announced that their blockade will not interfere with supplies
                    of food from the mainland to Kulangsu.</p>
                <p>Japanese press reports that there was increase in anti-Japanese activities in the
                    Settlement after the landing of American, British and French forces are without
                    foundation. Suggestions to this effect were made during the naval conferences
                    but the Japanese were unable to cite specific cases.</p>
                <p>Admiral Noble will leave for Shanghai today on the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Birmingham</hi> which is being succeeded by the British cruiser <hi
                        rend="italic">Cornwall</hi>. The British Ambassador arrived today on the <hi
                        rend="italic">Cornwall</hi> and will proceed to Shanghai on the <hi
                        rend="italic">Birmingham</hi>. It is expected that the U.S.S. <hi
                        rend="italic">Marblehead</hi> will leave for Shanghai tomorrow morning,
                    Captain Stapler, Commander of the South China Patrol, will transfer his flag to
                    the U.S.S. <hi rend="italic">Tulsa</hi> and sailors from the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Tulsa</hi> will replace the <hi rend="italic">Marblehead’s</hi> landing
                    force at the Consulate.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Chungking, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVitty</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
